about.aboutContent:
Stinging Insect Information

Can you tell them apart?


Bee

Hornet

Yellow Jacket


When stung by a stinging insect such as a bee, wasp, hornet, yellow jacket, or fire ant, most people experience a minor reaction to the venom injected at the sting site. However, some may experience a severe allergic reaction that can trigger anaphylaxis and result in death if not treated quickly.


Stinging insects found in Nova Scotia include: bees, wasps, hornets, yellow jackets, or fire ants. 


To reduce your chances of being stung: 

  • Stay away from insect nests

  • Wear long pants and sleeves

  • Avoid wearing scents



Minor symptoms of stings include:

  • local swelling

  • redness

  • itching

  • pain.

Severe reactions may cause more extensive swelling, hives, nausea, and anaphylaxis. 


First Aid for minor reactions to bee stings:

  • Remove stingers as soon as possible by scraping it off with a fingernail or card

  • Wash the sting area with soap and water

  • Apply a cold compress or ice pack

  • Avoid scratching the sting area - this worsens itching and swelling, as well as your risk of infection


In the case of a severe reaction, administer an epinephrine shot (“EpiPen” ®), take an oral antihistamine, and call 911.


More information: https://www.healthlinkbc.ca/health-topics/rt1285

widgets.label: Poison Ivy, Oak, and Sumac Information

about.aboutContent:
Poison Ivy, Oak, and Sumac Information
Poison Ivy 


Poison Oak

Poison Sumac

Poison Ivy, Poison Oak, and Poison Sumac are all seen in various regions of Canada with poison ivy growing across most of Nova Scotia. These plants cause allergic contact dermatitis in 85% of adults when they come into contact with the oil Urushiol found in their sap.


Contact with Urushiol can happen:

  • Directly: by touching the sap of the plants in which urushiol is present

  • Indirectly : contact with objects such as clothes or animals that have the oil stuck on their surface

  • Airborne: through burning the plant as the urushiol particles release into the air.


Symptoms include:

  • Redness

  • Severe Itching

  • Swelling

  • Blisters


Prevention:

  • Learn to identify the plants 

  • Avoid skin contact - wear long pants and sleeves

  • Do not burn plants you suspect are poison ivy, oak or sumac.


First Aid:

  • Wash with cold water

  • Can be treated with soothing lotions, or prescription medications for severe reactions


More information: https://ssl.eas.ualberta.ca/safety/?p=43

Black Bear Information

Black bears are the only species of bear that is native to Nova Scotia. While they can be found in most areas of the province, encounters with bears can be avoided by observing a few precautions.

The province of Nova Scotia suggests that hikers should:

  • Watch for signs of bear activity – tracks, scat, claw marks, hair on tree bark, or overturned rocks and logs.

  • Avoid areas bears may frequent – berry patches, rotting animal carcases and garbage dumps.

  • Make noise as you travel through the woods – talk, sing, carry a radio, wear a small bell, or rattle a pebble in an empty tin can.

  • Keep dogs leashed. If running loose, they can lead a bear back to you or provoke an attack.

If you do encounter a bear:

  • Stay calm

  •  Speak in a firm, authoritative voice and slowly back away - Do NOT climb a tree or run

  • Do not look the bear in the eyes or make threatening or sudden movements, unless you are attacked

If a bear attacks you: fight back! Do not play dead

For more information visit: https://novascotia.ca/natr/wildlife/nuisance/bears.asp

splash.splashContent:
Welcome to AllergeNS! This app was created to keep hikers with allergies safe while enjoying the great outdoors of Nova Scotia, Canada! All data used is available openly in Canada.


Disclaimer: This app is for educational purposes. If you are having a medical emergency, CALL 911 and follow operator instructions!

about.aboutContent:
Welcome to AllergeNS! The app that will keep you healthy while you explore the great outdoors of Nova Scotia.


AllergeNS takes crowd-sourced observations of common allergens that one could encounter while hiking, and informs the user of areas with particularly high sightings. The fact sheets for each allergen will help you properly identify risks while outdoors and in case of a medical emergency, the app will direct you to the nearest hospital (via road network). For the most up to date news on allergens and important resources in case of an emergency links to allergy related resources can be found to make your experience safe and enjoyable!


Functions:

Map area


Tap any hospital icon to get their address and contact information.


Top left corner


Tap one of these icons to see information about preventing encounters with these hazards, and what to do if you come across them.


Top right corner


 

Check out the "Select by group" tool and click the symbols to turn layers on or off - see just one group at a time or all of them at once!


Try the "Help me!" tool to locate the nearest hospital and get driving directions from any location in Nova Scotia.


 

Take a look at the important resources tab to get important phone numbers and government websites about allergies.


 

Change the basemap of the app to include satellite imagery or more labels.


If you like this app, don't forget to share with your friends using the "Share us" tool!


A word about our data:

AllergeNS was created using open source, citizen scientist observation data from iNaturalist via the Global Biodiversity Information Facility. You might notice concentrations of observations around towns and areas where people tend to frequent, and fewer points in very sparsely populated areas. This doesn't necessarily mean that these species don't exist in the areas where there are no observations - it just means they haven't been recorded in the database at this location (either because there are no bees at that place, or because there are no people there to observe them).


Citizen science is an important component of cataloguing the world, but these databases are by no means exhaustive. Please keep this in mind when using AllergeNS, and take precautions wherever you choose to travel, especially if you know you have severe allergies.



Product version: Online 7.4

Kernel version: 2.15

Important Resources 

Things to keep in your back pocket!

IN CASE OF AN EMERGENCY  -  CALL 911

811    -    Nova Scotia HealthLine     
A province-wide healthline with access to a healthcare professional to answer questions and give medical advice for any situation.

1-866-787-4050  -  Asthma & Allergy Helpline
Inquiries about asthma and respiratory allergies with an expert Certified Respiratory Edducator (CRE)

Canadian Society of Allergy and Clinical Immunology

Allergy research information
CSACI Doctors on Twitter for up to date allergy information
Follow them on twitter
